sections.text:
Nano-CT analysis was used to examine the pore connectivity of both sets of shale samples. Three-dimensional pore nets of the two shales samples were obtained to facilitate pore connectivity recognition. The pores in the Longmaxi shale samples were observed to have good connectivity (Fig. 9def). However, the pores in Niutitang shale samples were found to be poorly connected and isolated from each other (Fig. 10def), which is not favorable for shale gas exploration. Furthermore, based on the 3D pore nets and the pore distributions in the 3D samples, pores in the organic matter distributed in the surface of the shale samples (Fig. 9aec), we concluded that OM pores provide connectivity in the Longmaxi shale samples; this finding was confirmed by HIM images.
There are large amounts of OM pores with large sizes in the Longmaxi shale samples, which explain the good connectivity of this shale (Milliken et al., 2013). However, the pores in the Niutitang shale samples are mainly mineral matrix pores, including interP and intraP pores according to the HIM images, which were called dead-end pores, resulting in poor connectivity (Guo et al., 2015;
Wan et al., 2015). The nano-CT results confirm those obtained from the hysteresis loops of N2 adsorption and desorption. The Niutitang shale samples were found to contain many narrow slit-like pores in mineral matrix, which may cause the observed poor connectivity.
